{
  "text": "Putative associations among depression, tobacco smoking and nAChR function are best understood through the mechanisms of antidepressant drug actions [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Bupropion, an atypical antidepressant agent, has been found to be effective in reducing tobacco smoking in broard groups of patients, also including persons with depression [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Experimental studies have shown that bupropion blocks the activation of nAChRs by nicotine with some degree of selectivity, with the highest potency at 3 2 sites [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . The functional blocade of the nAChRs was non-competitive, and given the relative selectivity of bupropion at inhibiting 3 2 receptors which are implicated in nicotine-induced DA release from midbrain DA neurons (and thereby enhance its rewarding properties), the therapeutic efficacy of bupropion is partly explained. In addition to bupropion, other antidepressant drugs have been tested for their efficacy in promoting smoking cessation but only nortriptyline was shown to have significant beneficial effect [CITATION_7] . Although many of thes agents lacking therapeutic effect (e.g., selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors) also inhibit nAChRs at therapeutic concentrations [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] , one possible explanation for the discrepancy in clinical efficacy is that different nAChR subtypes are involved in mood regulation and nicotine dependence. It is likely that most antidepressant drugs affect the nAChR subtypes involved in modulating mood but only a few also affect nAChR subtypes involved in nicotine dependence [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] .",
